<subSubSection id="C36A6558FFA0FFF4FC9F36D7FAFFF7B3" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BCF36D3FFA0FFF4FC9F36D7FAFFF7B3" blockId="1.[832,1475,740,1468]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FC9F36D7FC7DF0F3" bold="true" box="[832,950,740,764]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C704D50FFA0FFF4FC1F36D6FB07F0F3" authorityName="Bertaco &amp; Cardoso" authorityYear="2005" box="[960,1228,741,764]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="malabarbai">
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FC1F36D6FB07F0F3" box="[960,1228,741,764]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">Microglanis malabarbai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from all other species in the genus by having a caudal fin that is almost completely black, with a narrow vertical white band across central portions of the caudal-fin rays. 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D50FFA0FFF4FA9F3776FC77F173" authorityName="Bertaco &amp; Cardoso" authorityYear="2005" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="malabarbai">
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FA9F3776FC77F173" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">Microglanis malabarbai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is further distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D50FFA0FFF4FB283756FAB0F173" baseAuthorityName="Boulenger" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[1271,1403,869,892]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cottoides">
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FB283756FAB0F173" box="[1271,1403,869,892]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">M. cottoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the longer head length (29.6-33.5 
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FBB637B6FB4DF193" box="[1129,1158,901,924]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">vs.</emphasis>
25.1-31.2% SL, 
<figureCitation id="134B2A56FFA0FFF4FAF337B6FAADF193" box="[1324,1382,901,924]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[151,190,866,890]" captionTargetBox="[154,755,193,832]" captionTargetId="graphics-483@3.[229,755,200,749]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 3. Regression of head length as function of standard length in M. malabarbai and two populations of M. cottoides. Note that 95% confidence intervals do not overlap with those of compared species indicating statistically significant difference." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5417578" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5417578/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), smaller pectoral spine length (17.0-22.5 
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FB463796FB7DF1B3" box="[1177,1206,933,956]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">vs.</emphasis>
20.0-27.5% SL), smaller maxillary barbel length (63.4-92.4 
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FB7E37F6FB76F1D3" box="[1185,1213,965,988]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">vs.</emphasis>
91.4-131.6% HL, Fig. 4), larger internareal distance (24.0-29.1 
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FB1837D6FB2FF1F3" box="[1223,1252,997,1020]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">vs.</emphasis>
19.6-25.2% HL, Fig. 5), and smaller number of lateral-line pores (6-7 
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FAE53036FA9CF613" box="[1338,1367,1029,1052]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">vs.</emphasis>
7-13, Fig. 6). It further differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D50FFA0FFF4FB853016FB07F633" authorityName="Malabarba &amp; Mahler" authorityYear="1998" box="[1114,1228,1061,1084]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cibelae">
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FB853016FB07F633" box="[1114,1228,1061,1084]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">M. cibelae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by longer head length (29.6-33.5 
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FC703076FC07F653" box="[943,972,1093,1116]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">vs.</emphasis>
25.1-28.9% SL), larger body width (29.3-33.1 
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FA793076FA09F653" box="[1446,1474,1093,1116]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">vs.</emphasis>
22.3-26.0% SL), and smaller maxillary barbel length (63.4-92.4 
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FC9F30B6FC96F693" box="[832,861,1157,1180]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">vs.</emphasis>
84.1-144.6% HL); from 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D50FFA0FFF4FBB430B6FB35F693" authorityName="Malabarba &amp; Mahler" authorityYear="1998" box="[1131,1278,1157,1180]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="eurystoma">
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FBB430B6FB35F693" box="[1131,1278,1157,1180]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">M. eurystoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by smaller mouth width (60.5-71.9 
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FC253096FBDCF6B3" box="[1018,1047,1189,1212]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">vs.</emphasis>
74.1-76.9% HL), and larger head depth (52.7-61.2 
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FC6C30F6FC1BF6D3" box="[947,976,1221,1244]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">vs.</emphasis>
42.4-48.2% HL); from 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D50FFA0FFF4FB1830F6FA92F6D3" box="[1223,1369,1221,1244]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="parahybae">
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FB1830F6FA92F6D3" box="[1223,1369,1221,1244]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">M. parahybae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by longer head length (29.6-33.5 
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FBEF30D6FB86F6F3" box="[1072,1101,1253,1276]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">vs.</emphasis>
23.2-27.6% SL), higher body depth (17.4-19.8 
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FC683136FC1FF713" box="[951,980,1285,1308]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">vs.</emphasis>
12.9-15.6% SL), and higher caudal peduncle depth (9.4-11.3 
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FC383116FBCFF733" box="[999,1028,1317,1340]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">vs.</emphasis>
7.6-9.7% SL); from 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D50FFA0FFF4FB013116FABEF733" authorityName="Bizerril &amp; Perez-Neto" authorityYear="1992" box="[1246,1397,1317,1340]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigripinnis">
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FB013116FABEF733" box="[1246,1397,1317,1340]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">M. nigripinnis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D50FFA0FFF4FA7A3116FCA0F753" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ater">
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FA7A3116FCA0F753" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">M. ater</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by color of fins (fins scattered with chromatophores 
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FA7A3176FA09F753" box="[1445,1474,1349,1372]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">vs.</emphasis>
all fins black, except caudal fin in 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D50FFA0FFF4FB243156FA7BF773" authorityName="Bertaco &amp; Cardoso" authorityYear="2005" box="[1275,1456,1381,1404]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="malabarbai">
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FB243156FA7BF773" box="[1275,1456,1381,1404]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">M. malabarbai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D50FFA0FFF4FC9F31B6FB8FF793" authorityName="Bertaco &amp; Cardoso" authorityYear="2005" box="[832,1092,1413,1436]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="malabarbai">
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FC9F31B6FB8FF793" box="[832,1092,1413,1436]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">Microglanis malabarbai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D50FFA0FFF4FADB31B6FA99F793" box="[1284,1362,1413,1436]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ater">
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FADB31B6FA99F793" box="[1284,1362,1413,1436]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">M. ater</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having a smaller number anal-fin rays (10-12 
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FB183196FB28F7B3" box="[1223,1251,1445,1468]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">vs.</emphasis>
14-15).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36A6558FFA0FFF7FC9F31D7FC0BF015" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="63" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BCF36D3FFA0FFF7FC9F31D7FE72F375" blockId="1.[832,1476,1508,1980]" lastBlockId="2.[159,803,195,538]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="63" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FC9F31D7FC11F7F3" bold="true" box="[832,986,1508,1532]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">Description.</emphasis>
Morphometric data for 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D50FFA0FFF4FAD231D6FA09F7F3" authorityName="Bertaco &amp; Cardoso" authorityYear="2005" box="[1293,1474,1509,1532]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="malabarbai">
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FAD231D6FA09F7F3" box="[1293,1474,1509,1532]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">M. malabarbai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
summarized in 
<tableCitation id="C6F20368FFA0FFF4FC3B3236FBFFF413" box="[996,1076,1541,1564]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="5.[151,214,194,218]" captionText="Table 1. Morphometric data of the holotype (H) and paratypes of Microglanis malabarbai (n = 11, including the holotype), and M. cottoides from rio Uruguay (n = 12) and rio Jacuí (n = 33) drainages, Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil." pageId="1" pageNumber="62">Table 1</tableCitation>
. Body compressed behind dorsal fin. Highest body depth at dorsal-fin origin, largest body width at pectoral-fin base. Head slightly depressed and rounded in dorsal view. Frontal fontanel small, nearly two times eye size. Supraoccipital process short, contacting pre-dorsal nuchal plate. Mouth curved, terminal; mouth gape about same size as head width at opercle. Teeth small and viliform. Premaxillary teeth in rectangular patch about four times wider than long. Dentary teeth patch along whole exposed border of dentary. Gill membranes free, supported by 8 or 9 branchiostegal rays; upper gill rakers of first arch 3 and lower gill rakers 7 (2 c&amp;s). Barbels thin, flattened in cross section. One maxillary and two mental pairs of barbels. Maxillary barbel short, not reaching base of pectoral-fin spines. Outer mental barbels longer than inner, and reaching base of pectoral-fin spines. Anterior nostril near upper lip, at tip of erect tube; posterior nostril near bony orbital margin. Eye closer to mouth than to distal margin of opercle. Lateral line with 6-7 pores (
<specimenCount id="9D76FD5AFFA3FFF7FD273510FECFF355" pageId="2" pageNumber="63" type="generic">one specimen</specimenCount>
with 9), reaching vertical line projected over base of last two dorsal-fin rays.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF0F665BFFA0FFF4FF48335FFF31F5CC" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5417570" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5417570" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5417570/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" startId="1.[151,189,1900,1924]" targetBox="[179,733,1435,1862]" targetPageId="1">
<paragraph id="8BCF36D3FFA0FFF4FF48335FFF31F5CC" blockId="1.[151,794,1900,1987]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FF48335FFF11F58B" bold="true" box="[151,218,1900,1924]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">Fig. 1.</emphasis>
Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil and Uruguay, with the known distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D50FFA0FFF4FEE533BFFE17F5AC" authorityName="Bertaco &amp; Cardoso" authorityYear="2005" box="[314,476,1932,1955]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="malabarbai">
<emphasis id="B904EAC1FFA0FFF4FEE533BFFE17F5AC" box="[314,476,1932,1955]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">M. malabarbai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(squares). Black bar: natural waterfall.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BCF36D3FFA3FFF7FF1B35B0FC0BF015" blockId="2.[159,803,195,538]" lastBlockId="2.[839,1483,195,538]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">
Dorsal fin with spinelet, strong pungent spine, and 5-6 soft branched rays. Spine short, smaller than soft rays, anterior margin smooth and posterior margin serrated in distal portion. Adipose fin of medium size, base longer than length of analfin base. Caudal fin emarginate, lower and upper lobes of equal length with rounded margins; principal caudal-fin rays 15-16 (mean = 15.5). Dorsal procurrent caudal-fin rays 15-16, and ventral procurrent caudal-fin rays 11-12. Anal fin short and rounded; posteriormost rays reaching caudal-fin base; anal-fin rays 10-12 (mean = 10.7), 3-4 unbranched, 7-8 branched. Pectoral fin with strong spine, 5 soft rays; anterior margin of spine with retrorse hooks on proximal third, antrorse hooks distally; and posterior margin with retrorse hooks along entire length. Posterior cleithral process slender and pointed. Pelvic fin rounded with i, 5 soft rays. Vertebral count 
<quantity id="4C889B36FFA3FFF7FAF035D0FA4CF3F5" box="[1327,1415,483,506]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.493" metricValueMax="7.62" metricValueMin="7.366" pageId="2" pageNumber="63" unit="in" value="29.5" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="29.0">29-30 in</quantity>
2 c&amp;s specimens.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
